<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-409-330  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 409 330.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  April 30 1990 v24 n18 p82(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>For security's sake, trust - but verify. (companies involved inalliances with other companies need to verify backgrounds andprotect their interests)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Davis, Leila.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Privacy and security experts urge companies to verify theiralliances before trusting other companies with private computerfiles.andP;  It is best to get as much electronic, legal and physicalprotection as possible and then rely on the good faith of thebusiness relationship for smooth operation of the alliance.andO;Software code that is developed in-house is often at risk; itsprotection may be overlooked if it is not part of the product orservice directly involved in the alliance.andP;  Early informationsystems (IS) involvement is of vital importance in defending acompany's information.andP;  A company will often want to keepnegotiations of a joint venture or other alliance confidentialuntil the final agreement is reached, so the IS director may notbe able to use IS staff on the project.andP;  An IS manager needs toknow what information is proprietary before the project begins.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     SecurityBusiness PlanningInformation Resources ManagementCooperative Agreement.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>